{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/accessibility-your-job/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"1Percent Blog  Kiran Anto"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"04dd909e-3c0c-59e6-8233-dc7bd771e9a5","excerpt":"Web accessibility is not just an afterthought of web development. This is something youâ€™ve to do as you create content, pages and applications on the web. Toâ€¦","html":"<p>Web accessibility is not just an afterthought of web development. This is something youâ€™ve to do as you create content, pages and applications on the web. To not think of accessibility is like discriminating people. Accessibility is making your application reach out to 100% of your user base, irrespective of their disabilities while browsing the web.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/9e0bb2017e3e93eea190c196b28239e2/72e01/mark.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 66.89189189189189%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Mark Zukerberg is Colorblind\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/9e0bb2017e3e93eea190c196b28239e2/1c72d/mark.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/9e0bb2017e3e93eea190c196b28239e2/a80bd/mark.jpg 148w,\n/static/9e0bb2017e3e93eea190c196b28239e2/1c91a/mark.jpg 295w,\n/static/9e0bb2017e3e93eea190c196b28239e2/1c72d/mark.jpg 590w,\n/static/9e0bb2017e3e93eea190c196b28239e2/a8a14/mark.jpg 885w,\n/static/9e0bb2017e3e93eea190c196b28239e2/72e01/mark.jpg 1024w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg is Color blind !! How do you show your website to him ?</p>\n<p>Yah, I know itâ€™s not very important, you can even create pages without taking care of these details. But the difference between good and great is attention to detail.</p>\n<h3 id=\"so-what-are-some-of-the-excuses-that-we-make-to-avoid-taking-care-of-accessibility\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#so-what-are-some-of-the-excuses-that-we-make-to-avoid-taking-care-of-accessibility\" aria-label=\"so what are some of the excuses that we make to avoid taking care of accessibility permalink\" class=\"header-links before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>So what are some of the excuses that we make to avoid taking care of accessibility?</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Accessibility is not cool</strong> ðŸ˜Ž</p>\n<p>Often times it is true, sometimes the fanciest UIâ€™s are not possible if we strictly stick to our accessibility guidelines. But what we should really think is that fancy UI is not always the best, itâ€™s the people who benefit from the product that matters. But if thereâ€™s a way we can circumvent this, Happy to.. (<a href=\"https://refactoringui.com/book/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Refactoring UI</a> by Adam Wathan &#x26; Steve Schoger, really gives some tips around this)</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Whatâ€™s the impact? We donâ€™t see an immediate effect.</strong></p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>People with disabilities do use the internet !! Not everyoneâ€™s perfect. Accessibility doesnâ€™t just help you improve the website for them, it just improves the usability of the website for everyone.</p>\n<ol start=\"3\">\n<li><strong>Not sure of what to do?</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Often times, yah most of us do not even think of this while creating a website, Sometimes itâ€™s when you actually see someone struggling to use the product or coming across the Accessibility concepts on the internet that we actually think of it. Itâ€™s the empathy that we should have for the users. You could get a lot of information on accessibility over the internet. You can get the general guideline here at - <a href=\"https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG20/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.0</a></p>\n<ol start=\"4\">\n<li><strong>Itâ€™s too hard, too much work !!</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Itâ€™s true that itâ€™s hard to think of every minor detail, different use cases. But itâ€™s worth it. It is even good for business by making it accessible to everyone.</p>\n<p>So I first started thinking about this after I saw someone colourblind, unable to identify success and failure messages on a website as they were just colour coded. One example of that could be seen here.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/6c014b88d21e1d002aca9b3381d80260/5a190/unaccessible_alerts.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 37.16216216216216%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"This is a really bad implementation, as users will struggle to identify at first sight.\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/6c014b88d21e1d002aca9b3381d80260/fcda8/unaccessible_alerts.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/6c014b88d21e1d002aca9b3381d80260/12f09/unaccessible_alerts.png 148w,\n/static/6c014b88d21e1d002aca9b3381d80260/e4a3f/unaccessible_alerts.png 295w,\n/static/6c014b88d21e1d002aca9b3381d80260/fcda8/unaccessible_alerts.png 590w,\n/static/6c014b88d21e1d002aca9b3381d80260/5a190/unaccessible_alerts.png 800w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p><em>This is a really bad implementation, as users will struggle to identify at first sight.</em></p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/8a2231e18560edbb7c2a292886360933/108f8/accessible_alerts.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 55.4054054054054%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Here atlaskit considers this case, so we have icons to help with understanding the content even before reading it.\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/8a2231e18560edbb7c2a292886360933/fcda8/accessible_alerts.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/8a2231e18560edbb7c2a292886360933/12f09/accessible_alerts.png 148w,\n/static/8a2231e18560edbb7c2a292886360933/e4a3f/accessible_alerts.png 295w,\n/static/8a2231e18560edbb7c2a292886360933/fcda8/accessible_alerts.png 590w,\n/static/8a2231e18560edbb7c2a292886360933/108f8/accessible_alerts.png 777w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p><em>Here atlaskit considers this case, so we have icons to help with understanding the content even before reading it.</em></p>\n<p>So after seeing these, i started reading up on accessibility. so as i progress iâ€™ll keep posting quick bits on accessibility.</p>\n<p>Enough of theory, letâ€™s talk that in detail in future.</p>\n<h3 id=\"so-what-are-some-of-the-areas-that-we-should-look-for-\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#so-what-are-some-of-the-areas-that-we-should-look-for-\" aria-label=\"so what are some of the areas that we should look for  permalink\" class=\"header-links before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>So what are some of the areas that we should look for ?</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Text readability</li>\n<li>Text overlaid on background images</li>\n<li>Colors, Filters etc</li>\n<li>Link recognition</li>\n<li>Color combinations</li>\n<li>Form placeholders and validations</li>\n<li>Primary Buttons</li>\n<li>Alert messaging</li>\n<li>Graphs</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Actually iâ€™ll put up some resources here if youâ€™re intrested in reading more on accessibility:</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.slideshare.net/TDdesign/how-to-design-for-colorblind-user\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Designing for a color blind user</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://amzn.to/3dhyiJv\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">How to Meet the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines 2.0</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://amzn.to/2zyLriY\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Web Accessibility: A Foundation for Research (Humanâ€“Computer Interaction Series)</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://medium.com/topic/accessibility\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Accessibility category on medium</a></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Adios for the day ðŸ‘‹</p>","timeToRead":2,"frontmatter":{"title":"â™¿ Accessibility is your job !!","date":"May 29, 2020","description":"Web accessibility is not just an afterthought of web development. This is something you've to do as you create content, pages and applications on the web. To not think of accessibility is like discriminating people. Accessibility is making your application reach out to 100% of your user base, irrespective of their disabilities while browsing the web."}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/accessibility-your-job/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/jamstack-p1/"},"timeToRead":2,"frontmatter":{"title":"Jamstack Conf 2020 Part 1 ðŸ”¥"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/a11y-visual-impairments/"},"timeToRead":2,"frontmatter":{"title":"â™¿ A11y: How can we improve the web experience for people with visual impairments?"}}}},"staticQueryHashes":["2841359383","3182425314"],"slicesMap":{}}